Here's the pattern using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — override `CreateWindow` and use a custom `Window` subclass:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", notePage.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
        {
            notePage.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped, so save here too
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", notePage.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key things to know:**

1. **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded (not visible). This is where you save.
2. **`OnResumed`** fires when the app returns from `Stopped`. This is where you restore.
3. **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because on Android the back button can skip `Stopped` entirely and go straight to `Destroying`.
4. **`OnResumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created → Activated`. Load any persisted draft in your page's `OnAppearing` or constructor instead.
5. **Keep handlers fast** (<1–2 seconds). `Preferences` is ideal for small values like draft text. Avoid database writes here — Android enforces a ~5s ANR timeout and iOS has a background watchdog.
